BLUE HAIR! /prance <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uatuaritanaquil99.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AtuariTanaquil99</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#E9D756>(8/3/02 5:07:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=10255.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Interesting.</span><hr size=1> My husband and I started playing EQ when a friend of ours described the game to us.  We were somewhat skeptical and thought he was a freak =p but decided to give it a try.  At the time we had one computer and bought one copy of the game.  When we both decided we liked the game we got another copy of the game and then eventually another computer and another… I kept my character from the first account because I was higher in level and he re started his character.  Due to our level difference we never really grouped together, we were in separate guilds at first, and we had our own set of friends.  <br>
<br>
But as we both got higher in level we joined the same guild and made many mutual friends.  It was really fun to finally start grouping together after 60+ levels hehe.  Currently we are both in the same guild, have 6 different accounts, 5 computers, and we play eq about 50+ hours per week.  Its fun to share the same hobby (addiction) and have someone who understands EQ, I couldn’t imagine playing this much if my significant other did not…. <br>
<br>
In sum, the ideal situation IMO is not only to have your significant other play EQ, but to play it with the same level of commitment that you do.<br>
<br>
<br>
